        <section class="prose mt-8">
          <h2>What is SRM in beer?</h2>
          <p>
            SRM (Standard Reference Method) is the most common scale used in North America to describe beer color.
            It is based on how much light a beer sample absorbs at a wavelength of 430&nbsp;nm in a 1&nbsp;cm cuvette.
            Low SRM values indicate very pale beers, while high SRM values indicate very dark beers.
          </p>

          <div class="formula-box">
            <strong>Laboratory definition</strong><br>
            \( \text{SRM} = 12.7 \times A_{430} \)<br>
            where \(A_{430}\) is the absorbance of the beer at 430&nbsp;nm in a 1&nbsp;cm path length.
          </div>

          <h3>SRM vs EBC vs Lovibond</h3>
          <p>Brewers often need to convert between three related color scales:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>SRM</strong> – Standard Reference Method (North America).</li>
            <li><strong>EBC</strong> – European Brewing Convention (Europe and many commercial malts).</li>
            <li><strong>Lovibond (°L)</strong> – Older visual color scale, still used for malt specifications.</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="formula-box">
            <strong>Practical conversion formulas</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>\( \text{EBC} \approx 1.97 \times \text{SRM} \)</li>
              <li>\( \text{SRM} \approx 0.508 \times \text{EBC} \)</li>
              <li>For typical brewing ranges, Lovibond is close to SRM: \( \text{SRM} \approx \text{°L} \)</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-0">
              Note: At very high colors the relationships become non‑linear; this calculator uses the standard linear approximations
              that are accurate for most homebrew and craft beer recipes.
            </p>
          </div>

          <h2>Estimating beer color from your grain bill (Morey equation)</h2>
          <p>
            In recipe design, we rarely measure absorbance directly. Instead, we estimate SRM from the grain bill using
            MCU (Malt Color Units) and an empirical correction known as the Morey equation.
          </p>

          <h3>Step 1 – Calculate MCU</h3>
          <p>For US units (pounds and gallons):</p>
          <div class="formula-box">
            \( \displaystyle \text{MCU} = \frac{\sum ( \text{weight}_i \text{ [lb]} \times \text{color}_i \text{ [°L]} )}{\text{volume [gal]}} \)
          </div>
          <p>For metric units (kilograms and liters), a common approximation is:</p>
          <div class="formula-box">
            \( \displaystyle \text{MCU} \approx \frac{\sum ( \text{weight}_i \text{ [kg]} \times \text{color}_i \text{ [EBC]} )}{\text{volume [L]} \times 8.345} \)
          </div>

          <h3>Step 2 – Apply the Morey equation</h3>
          <p>The Morey equation corrects MCU to better match real-world SRM measurements:</p>
          <div class="formula-box">
            \( \displaystyle \text{SRM} = 1.4922 \times \text{MCU}^{0.6859} \)
          </div>
          <p>
            This formula works well for most beers up to about 50&nbsp;SRM. Above that, perceived color differences become small
            and the estimate is less critical.
          </p>

