          <h2>FAQ about SRM and beer color</h2>
          <h3>Is SRM the same as Lovibond?</h3>
          <p>
            Not exactly. Lovibond (°L) is an older visual color scale, while SRM is based on spectrophotometric measurement.
            For pale to moderately dark beers, SRM and Lovibond values are often very close, so many homebrew recipes treat them
            as interchangeable. At higher colors, the difference becomes more noticeable.
          </p>

          <h3>How accurate is the Morey SRM estimate?</h3>
          <p>
            The Morey equation is an empirical fit to real beer data and is widely used in brewing software.
            It is generally accurate enough for recipe design, especially for beers under about 50&nbsp;SRM.
            Actual color can still vary with mash pH, boil time, caramelization, and fermentation effects.
          </p>

          <h3>Should I use SRM or EBC?</h3>
          <p>
            Use whichever matches your references and local standards. If your malt specs are in EBC and style guidelines in SRM,
            this calculator makes it easy to convert between them. The underlying beer color is the same; only the scale changes.
          </p>
